AB  - An Analysis of the Congolese Rural Economy in the Interwar Years
   The Belgian Congo experienced radical socioeconomic change in the Interwar years. From the 1920s, the mining industry expanded, replacing agricultural produce as the Colony's principal export. At the same time, it saw the introduction of capitalist forms of agriculture to the agrarian sector. As a consequence of these transitions, some authors have argued that a "dual" economy evolued, in which market and non-marked forms of agriculture were separated. However, this article argues that, rather than a static dual economy, a dynamic "hybrid" form emerged in which market and non-market forms of production were joined.
   The first part of the article analyses the types of agriculture present in the Belgian Congo : collectives, Cultures obligatoires ('Compulsery cultivations') introduced in 1917, plantations, smallholdings and the Paysannats indigenes ('Indigerous peasant culturations') introduced in 1936. The second section demonstrates that the assimilation of the Congolese population was often accompanied by coercion, and sometimes violence, and led to a decline in collective agriculture. The Congolese population resisted, but was forced to develop new strategies to survive. Part of the local population switched from agriculture at a large-scale communal level to working in small-scale household types, in a process known as "Peasantification". The final part of the article emphasizes that, as a result of this change, a dynamic interaction developed between capitalist and non-capitalist forms of production in the Interwar years. This was possible because of the flexibility of the Congolese farmers, who were able to combine subsistence agriculture with (industrial or agrarian) wage labor. Considering these findings, looking at the Congolese economy as dual is unhelpful and misleading.
